ated as \"Just as you rejected us, we thoroughly reject you. We even reject the dust from your city that clings to our feet.\" Since Jesus was sending these people out in groups of two, it would be two people saying this. So languages that have a dual form of 'we' would use it. (See: [[en:ta:vocabulary:pluralpronouns]])"}, {"ref": "But know this, that the kingdom of God had drawn near", "text": "This phrase introduces a warning. It means \"Even though you reject us, it does not change the fact that the kingdom of is here!\""}, {"ref": "the kingdom of God has drawn near", "text": "\"the kingdom of God is all around you.\""}, {"ref": "I say to you", "text": "Jesus was saying this to the 70 people he was sending out. He said this to show that he was about to say something very important."}, {"ref": "the judgment day", "text": "The phrase simply says \"that day.\" But the disciples would have understood that this refers to the time of final judgment of sinners. (See: [[:en:ta:discourse:implicitexplicit]])"}, {"ref": "it will be more tolerable for Sodom, than for that city", "text": "\"Sodom will not be judged as severely as that city will be judged.\" This means \"that city will be judged more severely than Sodom.\""}]}, {"id": "10-13", "tn": [{"ref": "", "text": "(Jesus turns from speaking to the 70 disciples and speaks to the people of three cities.)"}, {"ref": "Woe to you Chorazin! Woe to you Bethsaida", "text": "Jesus speaks as if the people of the cities of Chorazin and Bethsaida were there listening to him, but they were not. (See: [[:en:ta:figuresofspeech:apostrophe]])"}, {"ref": "if the mighty works which were done in you", "text": "This can be translated with an active verb as it is in the UDB: \"If the miracles that I had performed for you.\" (See: [[en:ta:vocabulary:active]])"}, {"ref": "were done in Tyre and Sidon", "text": "This can be translated with an active verb: \"if someone had done them in Tyre and Sidon.\""}, {"ref": "they would have repented long a