\""}, {"ref": "to the rule and to the authority of the governor", "text": "\"Rule\" and \"authority\" are two ways of saying the same thing. It can be translated with one or both expressions. The reason for handing Jesus over to the governor can be made explicit: \"so that the governor would punish Jesus.\""}]}, {"id": "20-21", "tn": [{"ref": "but you teach the truth about the way of God", "text": "This is part of what the spy was saying that they knew about Jesus."}, {"ref": "are not influenced by anyone", "text": "Possible meanings are 1) \"you tell the truth even if important people do not like it\" (UDB) or 2) \"you do not favor one person over another.\""}, {"ref": "Is it lawful to pay taxes to Caesar", "text": "They hoped that Jesus would say either \"yes\" or \"no.\" If he said \"yes,\" then the Jewish people would be angry with him for telling them to pay taxes to a foreign government. If he said \"no,\" then the religious leaders could tell the Romans that Jesus was teaching the people to break the Roman laws."}, {"ref": "Is it lawful", "text": "They were asking about God's law, not about Caesar's law. This can also be translated \"Does our law permit us.\""}, {"ref": "Caesar", "text": "Because Caesar was the ruler of the Roman government, they could refer to the Roman government by Caesar's name. (See: [[en:ta:figuresofspeech:metonymy]])"}]}, {"id": "20-23", "tn": [{"ref": "But Jesus understood their craftiness", "text": "\"But Jesus understood how tricky they were\" or \"But Jesus saw that they were trying to trap him\""}, {"ref": "image and superscription", "text": "\"picture and name\""}]}, {"id": "20-25", "tn": [{"ref": "He said to them", "text": "\"Then Jesus said to them\""}, {"ref": "Caesar", "text": "\"Caesar\" refers to the Roman government. (See: [[en:ta:figuresofspeech:metonymy]])"}, {"ref": "were not able to criticize what he said", "text": "\"could not find anything wrong with what he said\""}, {"ref": "They marveled", "text": "\"They were sur